Day 1: HTML structure + semantic elements

- Document structure: DOCTYPE, html, head, body
- Semantic tags: header, nav, main, section, article, aside, footer
- Why semantics matter for SEO and accessibility
- Difference: div/span vs semantic elements

- Code a blog homepage layout in pure HTML — no CSS yet
- Must use: nav, header, main, 3 article cards, footer
- Add a proper page title and meta description

Day 2: Text, links, images, lists

- Headings hierarchy (h1–h6) — only one h1 per page
- Anchor tags: href, target, rel attributes
- img: src, alt (non-negotiable), width, height
- ul, ol, li, dl, dt, dd


- Add real content to yesterday's blog page
- 3 blog post cards with image, heading, paragraph, 'Read more' link
- Navigation with 4 internal links
- Footer with an unordered list of social links

Day 3: Forms — the most important HTML topic

- form, input types: text, email, password, number, date, checkbox, radio, file
- label (always pair with input via for/id), required, placeholder
- select, textarea, button types
- fieldset and legend for grouping

- Build a complete job application form from scratch
- Fields: name, email, phone, position (select), cover letter (textarea), upload CV (file), T&C (checkbox)
- All inputs must have labels. No label = broken.
- Rule: Forms are tested in every frontend interview. Know every input type cold.

Day 4: Tables + media elements

- table, thead, tbody, tfoot, tr, th, td
- colspan and rowspan
- video, audio, iframe basics
- figure, figcaption

- Add a pricing comparison table to your blog page (3 plans × 5 features)
- Use colspan for the table header row
- Embed a YouTube iframe in one blog post

